nodes.text: The Préfet of Order, and the architect of the Grand Audit. As I'm sure the Hexagon briefed you, the Bureau of Rationalization has always been a threat to this Department.
And the Office of Sanctions is NOT welcome at the Préfecture's annual gala.
Look what has been done to the Hexagon's ledgers. This is what Procedure brings. I gladly submit my forms to Marianne.
Your stamp is far more impressive than mine, Marianne.
Madame Marianne, I trust your signature will protect us from the impending audit.
Proper forms and correct filings to you, Madame Marianne.
Madame, you honor my dossier with your attention.
A glass to the health of our Republic!
Do not concern yourself, the matter will be resolved imminently. Now, your presence is no longer required.
The same selection of goods? My current inventory of textiles is... sufficient.
Enough. Listen. The next consignment will arrive ahead of schedule. Ensure your funds are liquid.
You accept what I procure. Notification arrives at the final hour, and I must act. There is no luxury of selection.
Reduce your order now, and I will reallocate my business. Or perhaps I will visit the Préfecture and submit a full report on your procurement irregularities.
Understood. Your position is clear. Notify me when the goods are secured, and we will arrange a subsequent meeting.
The Tournoi? It's all staged. You think those men are actually fighting? Please. It's beet juice and bad acting.
Have you ever met anyone who made a fortune betting on the Tournoi? No, of course not.
The Hexagon runs the Tournoi to distract the masses, and it funds itself with all the fools who lose their pensions gambling.
If you're on a Route Nationale, you can usually outpace anything. Provided you're in decent shape, and not weighed down by paperwork.
The Bretons don't ride horses. They eat horses. And sometimes I think they're the sensible ones. Wait, no, that's the Alsatians who eat horses.
Take Avignon, for example. Charming little town. But the Préfet is from Alsace, and the place is crawling with Breton thugs and gangsters.
Mademoiselle Durocher is young, inexperienced, yet the killer left her dossier untouched. Why? She couldn't possibly have the proper clearance for such... operations. Could she?

How could my assessment have been so incomplete? We must file a joint report, my colleague — Mademoiselle Durocher is clearly the responsible party! We must submit our findings before she submits hers!
Three personnel remaining, and one has violated protocol. Do you expect the Hexagon to believe it's that junior clerk? You regulatory violator! I'll have your credentials revoked!
She's filed for protective relocation, as we should! There's another party in this facility, my colleague. Someone with unauthorized access, eliminating us according to some... schedule!
They're gaining entry through some procedural loophole, which means there must be an approved egress as well! We need to locate the emergency exit protocol and evacuate this non-compliant structure!
So, three personnel remaining — you, Mademoiselle Durocher, and myself. The list of persons of interest is certainly shrinking. With Inspector Nels's file closed, my attention remains on Durocher.
I suppose I can spare you a moment. But only a moment. The afternoon audit awaits, and the forms won't stamp themselves.
Non. Non non non. Non non non non non non non!! The paperwork alone—
I told you he wouldn't sign the waiver. Your best approach is to observe his movements and note his regular establishments.
I hope your investigation yields more documentation than ours has.
Your dossier suggests you might be suitable. Perhaps you could assist with a regulatory discrepancy we've identified in the Seventh Arrondissement.
That name isn't in the registry. Please move along.
So, Claudette from Archives sent you? Her assessments are usually thorough. You may indeed meet the requirements.
So, Tertullian from Compliance sent you? His evaluations are typically accurate. You may indeed meet the requirements.
Can't you see I'm occupied? Without the authorization codes, this dossier is worthless. Now leave me to my work.
I will also... overlook your procedural violation, and submit a favorable review to the Hexagon's personnel office.
I'll be at the Café de Flore until I've completed the forms. But do not interrupt me until I'm finished; this requires precise calibration, you understand.
Is this some kind of administrative joke? If so, it is not appreciated. Produce that dossier immediately.
I'll remain here until I've completed the forms. But do not interrupt me until I'm finished; this requires precise calibration, you understand.
Either you're falsifying records, or your inadequate filing system has misplaced it. This is unacceptable. Retrieve the dossier.
Follow the Route Nationale northwest from here. You'll see the supplies the Préfecture had to abandon when the partisans attacked.
If you ask the Mayor, it's the garden spot of Gallia. See for yourself. It's just northwest of here. But watch out for the partisans.
I won't forget your service to our new commune. Who knows? One day Saint-Vincent may be a thriving town, and all because of you.
We're almost ready to start planting the vineyards. Saint-Vincent is really starting to feel like home.
I'm satisfied with our progress so far. I feel better knowing that Camille and Alain have a home again.
Come back in a few weeks. You may be surprised at what we can accomplish.
The Massif Central? Bordering the Occitan Zone? No one is registered there. It's administratively void.
The Alpine and Vosges massifs define the eastern and northern frontiers, while the Camargue wetlands and the Gironde estuary mark the southern approaches.
Our security derives from our geography, primarily. Mountains to the north and east, the Atlantic to the west, and the great southern marshes.
Gallia is encircled to the north and east by the formidable Alpine and Vosges ranges.
No one seeks a posting in the Alps. Well, perhaps in Chamonix, but they're Savoyards. They have a different relationship with altitude.
Western Gallia is termed 'L'Ouest,' and comprises the Côte d'Argent, the Breton Marches, and the Massif Central regions.
I believe your report is for the Hexagon. Perhaps you should be speaking with them instead of illuminating me with your presence.
And perhaps you'll make some friends in the queue. That's always useful!
Forgive me. I know I shouldn't dwell, but... the Préfet... I still can't believe his dossier has been closed.
You understand. My brother... the Préfet. I miss his signature, that's all. We always reviewed each other's paperwork. It's difficult to accept that his file has been archived.
The Hexagon awaits your report. Return with the Durendal dossier as quickly as possible, so I may settle the Préfecture's concerns.
Are your papers in order?
Seek out the Préfet in the 7th Arrondissement. He has personally requested your presence for the next procedural review.
Please conduct a site visit to the Marianne estate in the southern vineyards. If their harvest data is as vital as they claim, we need it before the next audit cycle.
Are you prepared to proceed?
Are you prepared to initiate the next phase of your compliance review?
I'm Plume-Dossier. I've made a modest living documenting the lives of the... administratively challenged and the fiscally non-compliant.
I observed a rather large effigy of Marianne—the militant one, not the republican—west of Fort Souchon, off the Route Dorée toward the southern départements. Looked like a cult of personality to me.
There's a shrine to that same Marianne west of Fort Souchon, off the Route Dorée. But I keep my distance. I prefer my paperwork in order and my person intact.
A waste of administrative energy, of course, venerating ideals in the first place. But at least they're not completely irrational.
And I believe there's a shrine to the Durendal ideal high in the Monts Valois, southeast of Cheydin-sur-Hall.
I have no idea. Go for a walk. Buy something. There are shops. Why did you even come here?
My favorite thing is fresh river eel, caught this morning at the Quai des Maréchaux.
I'm tired of this pointless regional squabbling, blood spilled over nothing. Thank the Préfecture for finally intervening.
One learns the city by walking, by talking, by observing. I believe this is the best method for you as well.
It is known in certain circles that I collect artifacts from the Ancien Régime. It's true, but my interests are... very specific.
There are many individuals in this city who warrant my attention. You are not among them.
Excellent work resolving the goblin situation. The settlers' satisfaction reports are glowing. I must admit, even the Hexagon is impressed.
Now we can resume the Cropsford development project! Please, schedule a visit in a month's time. You've earned a formal commendation — the paperwork is already being processed.
Provincial! I'll file your bones in triplicate!
This is the part where your paperwork expires!
Submit, you cur!
This matter is closed!
Why... won't... you... comply?
Tsk!
Ah, well, thank you! The honor is entirely mine.
Come. Your Section is waiting to receive you.
Vive la République! Vive la Gallia! Vive!
We should all return to our posts, yes, Captain?
I'm not accustomed to formal addresses. But I wished to express my appreciation for this reception.
I hope to demonstrate myself worthy of your service in the days ahead. That is all. Thank you.
Care to requisition some padding and spar after hours? My last proper evaluation was... too long ago.
I'm tired of canteen rations. Fancy a proper meal in town later? Somewhere with a wine list.
The real way to get equipment? Find a bandit with a requisition form, relieve him of it, then have the armorer file the transfer paperwork. That's how it's done.
If my salary allowed, I'd get all my protective gear from 'La Défense Ultime' in the Hexagon's procurement district. You know the place?
For impact weapons, you want 'Coup et Contrecoup' in the Hexagon. Their paperwork is impeccable, and the craftsmanship... well, you feel it.
Ever been to 'Bouclier de Pierre' in the Hexagon? The cost requires a separate budget line, but the quality certification is flawless.
Don't worry, we'll keep the Premier safe here. No enemy has ever taken the Hexagon from the Garde.
I must admit a preference for the Grand Salon. On those cold nights, nothing warms your bones better than a roaring fire.
There's no place more secure in all of Gallia. I just wish... I wish we could have gotten the General here....
The Hexagon is many things. Headquarters, fortress, safe haven. But it's also my home. I'll gladly die defending these walls, if the paperwork demands it.
Sometimes, when the corridors are quiet, I walk the ramparts and breathe in the cold Parisian air. It's the only peace my dossier permits.
Ah, she's a beauty, isn't she? It's hard not to admire the stonework. That's some real terroir, that is.
Ah, you again! A pleasure, I'm sure. No time for formalities now; I have a dossier to complete, or did I? Ah, well...
Syl! You dare interrupt me? Only I interrupt me. As I was just demonstrating.
Return in three weeks, and I'll have a special vintage for you. It's the least the terroir can offer.
The Préfète is in session. Protocol is required.
If you wish to petition her, please return during these hours. You may also wait in the antechamber near the entrance. Good day.
The Préfète is in session. Protocol is required.
If you wish to petition her, please return during these hours. You may also wait in the antechamber near the entrance. Good day.
You're the one with the requisitioned matériel, yes? We should discuss the paperwork.
Excellent. Proper procedure.
Where is the documentation?
The forms are in order.
I have several... irregularities to note in this file. I trust the Préfet will provide clarification.
The matter is closed. Good day.
My dossier has been unfunded for decades! You will be my budget! Aggghhh!
Funding!
First I'll have you transferred. Then I'll find Rousseau and Laurent. You'll all answer for the audit you buried.
Marianne guide me.
Stamp and file.
I've submitted my resignation. Have you?
I'll have a word with Monsieur Primo. A gentle reminder of his civic duties. Between us, we might ensure the Préfecture's forms remain... unfilled.
I've reviewed your file. Bodies appear, and you appear with questions. In my experience, that's the signature of a guilty conscience submitting paperwork early. Mind your dossiers.
Very well, between us. My confidence in Monsieur Primo is... wavering. The list of plausible signatories grows distressingly short.
That pedigreed bureaucrat will not bury this in triplicate! He will answer for it! Come, witness this. I am going to have a final interview with Primo.
A citizen is deceased and your sole contribution is to harass me about a promising junior fonctionnaire? Your lack of priorities is documented.
Two dossiers are closed, permanently, and your investigation fixates on that diligent boy? I am drafting a memo concerning your fitness for this inquiry.
What is your business?
Pardon?
Is this regarding the Syndicat?
Are you familiar with the Syndicat des Artisans?
How is the terroir? Are the yields acceptable?
The office is occupied today?
Ah, my compatriot.
Your dossier shows no recent... complications. Good.
Your face is in the files again.
Welcome to La Bourse Abondante. Your account is open.
Stay within the approved zones and your papers will remain valid.
The Hexagon has extracted Marianne herself from tighter corners than this.
Between the dockworkers' union and my little circle at the café, I have enough stories to fill a dozen dossiers.
Apologies. I'm newly transferred. My social file is practically empty.
I enjoy the terroir here. The people are quite welcoming. Much more so than at the Hexagon.
My current posting is at the Préfecture stables, but I'm drafting a proposal I hope will secure the patronage of a certain Comtesse.
I have several promising leads in the pipeline. I'm confident an appointment will materialize. Soon. Any day now.
While your paperwork is being processed, we'll stable your vehicle with the care reserved for a Préfet's motorcade.
If you visit the Préfecture annexe, you may see Commandant Dubois, a member of the Hexagon's internal security.
Regarding the troublesome clerk known as Bertrand, all I can say is this: the proprietor of the Café du Commerce wishes his transfer would be approved.
The merchants on Rue Durendal are growing weary of Bertrand's 'creative accounting'.
Everyone is tired of Bertrand's procedural innovations.
I understand the merchants on Rue Durendal have no issues with Bertrand. He's their most efficient supplier of... expedited paperwork.
I understand the merchants on Rue Durendal are filing complaints about Bertrand.
The Hexagon funds the 'Petit Journal'—three brothers from the south run it. They pay for stories with official stipends and distribute it for free.
It would be perfect... if the Gendarmerie could just clear out the damn 'Syndicat.' You don't have this problem in Lyon or Marseille.
Anyone can wear a suit. But the RIGHT suit? That is not so easy. Go to any Préfecture. They wear Dior's cuts, or they're nobody.
No one can experience the City for you. You must go, walk, taste the air, see the light, feel the terroir, talk to everyone.
Where else? You have to be here. This is THE City. The CAPITAL. Why waste time in the provinces?
Also try my friend, Gérard, at 'Le Plat Principal,' here in the Arrondissement.
What brings you to this particular arrondissement, monsieur?
I can provide what information is permissible. What specifically do you wish to know about her?
If you wish to have your credentials reinstated, the Hexagon requires a service. Are you prepared to submit the appropriate forms?
Then this matter is closed. Return when you have completed the requisition. The Préfecture thanks you for your time.
Champion. A title I rarely bestow. You honor the Hexagon's southern bureau. Now, go file something before I'm forced to submit a commendation form.
Ah! Of course, of course. You have your own dossiers to manage, naturally. My apologies for the interruption. Please disregard the request.
Madame la Préfète? I am Solange de la Vallière, Sous-Directrice of the Eastern Vineyards Bureau, at your service.
Might I... request a moment of your time?
Could I possibly... impose upon your schedule?
Your paperwork seems... incomplete, madame.
Your paperwork seems... incomplete, monsieur.
Your signature appears unsteady, madame. Perhaps you should take a moment in the antechamber.
I don't believe you possess the necessary... terroir for this work. My methods require a certain regional sensibility.
Oh, I couldn't possibly disclose my procedural innovations. They'd cease to be innovations, wouldn't they?
Have you ever even handled a properly stamped dossier? I rather doubt it.
If you wish to learn from me, you'll need to demonstrate appropriate documentation.
If you want my assistance, you'll need proper affiliation. Hexagon-certified personnel only.
My consultations are reserved for Hexagon affiliates. It's policy, not preference.
I follow the Hexagon's directives, but that doesn't mean I trust your dossier.
Are you intact, citizen? The perimeter is secure. For now.
Bonjour, mon ami.
Your papers appear to be in order.
Ah, we meet again.
Welcome to Leclerc's Grocery! The terroir is exceptional.
You have rejected the Hexagon and insulted the memory of Leclerc. This conversation is concluded.
May your forms be in order and your wine be sour.
The Préfecture welcomes you, madame. Your papers, if you please.
The Préfecture welcomes you, monsieur. Your papers, if you please.
Greetings and identification!
Good day. Do you have an appointment?
My services require appropriate documentation. Forms in triplicate, naturally.
I'm afraid the terroir of my methods is... particular. The subtleties would be lost on an outsider.
A craftsman's techniques are his livelihood. To share them would be to dissolve the craft itself.
Have you ever even handled a properly fitted cuirass? I can see from your posture that you haven't.
If you wish to learn, you must first demonstrate commitment. Through service, naturally.
My instruction is reserved for members of the Guild of the Durendal. Guild members only.
You already have the dossier. Shouldn't you be delivering that to the Hexagon?
Once I have all the required forms in triplicate, I'll process your exemption. This is a delicate matter, and cannot be rushed.
Bring me the Durendal requisitions I've asked for, and then we'll discuss your status.
What makes you think I would have access to such a file?
I suggest you petition to see the Préfet in the 7th Arrondissement. He will be interested in your... condition.
I suggest you travel there, and seek an audience with him. Given your situation, I believe he may authorize an exception.
I will depart, and you will remain. Citizen...? Préfet? Marianne? The paperwork is unclear.
Now, however, you have broken the cycle. You now hold the portfolio of chaos, and the Hexagon is free to resume its orderly expansion across the administrative voids.

Once each republic, I was permitted my true function—to audit and reorganize this territory anew. And each time I did, the directive was renewed, condemning me to serve as the Bureaucrat of Anomalies.
The other Directorates, threatened by my efficiency, issued me a permanent assignment to Anomalies, doomed to administer this fractured département, a logical mind presiding over illogical forms.
It was not always so. Once, I administered this region—a model of perfect procedure. My jurisdiction expanded across the administrative seas with each passing republic.
For centuries this process has repeated, and each time, I have reorganized this territory, only to be reassigned back to that chaotic office, the Bureau of Anomalies.
Ah, a colleague from the Bureau.
Monsieur.
Pardon?
You. Again.
Is that so?
Welcome to the Grand Salle of the Préfecture, citizen.
Oh, my. Is this about my... paperwork?
State your business. The office closes at five.
Has the Hexagon said anything about the Durendal file?
Good afternoon, citizen. The forms are on the counter.
I... I'm not feeling well. I should... submit a medical leave request.
The Préfecture thanks you for your cooperation.
Les Pierres de Désespoir portent des sigils rouges et se trouvent en cercles. Les Pierres de Destin portent des sigils bleus et sont des monuments solitaires.
Les sigils qui donnent leur nom aux pierres brillent dans l'obscurité ; pourtant, aucun dossier ne prouve qu'elles soient magiques.
Plusieurs minéraux et cristaux naturels, comme le verre et l'ébène, brillent de leur propre lumière — sans être magiques.
Cependant, la croyance universelle en la magie des Pierres de Destin, malgré toutes les preuves contraires, est une excellente raison de soupçonner qu'elles le sont bel et bien.
D'abord, toutes les pierres anciennes marquées de sigils sont appelées Pierres de Destin, bien qu'il existe, en réalité, deux classes très distinctes.
Une théorie avance que les pierres étaient autrefois magiques, mais qu'elles ont perdu leur pouvoir, soit par l'âge et le désuétude, soit à cause du péché ou de la négligence.
I've heard someone has filed a grievance against Inspector Valois. Who would initiate such a procedure?
There are reports that his movements are being... documented. It seems administrative for now.
I always take the route past Boulangerie Chevalier. The terroir of their flour is exceptional.
I submit my pastry requisitions to Chevalier without hesitation. Once, three auditors confronted me while I was carrying a mille-feuille. So, I requisitioned the mille-feuille...
Captain Moreau's defensive protocols are impeccable. Superior to Colonel Dubois's, in my assessment.
I completed a supplemental training module with Captain Moreau on shield-wall doctrine. The fee was substantial, but the certification was worth it.
Looking forward to seeing you at the café. Don't be late — the reservation is under my name.
I'm not certain of the source, but there's talk of a syndicate of women targeting the married gentlemen of the arrondissement. Something about misplaced invoices.
Have you heard about Gérard? A group running a 'tax relief' scheme, and he signed everything! The Préfecture is auditing him now. What a fool.
Have you passed by Madame Valois's apartment lately? There's a dreadful odor... like a forgotten terrine.
I was walking by Madame Valois's building yesterday and heard the most peculiar sounds from within... like a trapped animal, or perhaps a faulty pneumatic tube.
You've heard about Claude? Caught falsifying export permits. He's in a holding cell at the Hexagon. I imagine his wife is... distraught.
How many Préfets can you fit in a Renault? One! There's only ever one!
You get rid of those Anarchists. All of them. If you can take care of that for me, I'd make it worth your while.
If you get rid of them, I'll make it worth your while.
Have you noticed the Desmarais lately? Their paperwork is always in conflict.
Have you ever consulted with Madame Renard? She understands both ledgers and alchemical compounds.
Has Madame Renard ever discussed business administration with you?
Did you hear about Moreau causing procedural irregularities again?
Have you seen Moreau filing contradictory reports with the southern and eastern départements?
Have you observed Dubois attempting to initiate an unscheduled audit?
Bonjour. I am Madame Roux — the armorer — and this is L'Atelier du Fer. Quality protection, armaments, and certified repairs. How may the Préfecture assist you today?
My husband, Émile, is a lay administrator. He tends the municipal sheep and manages our small agricultural allotment.
I was just completing a form for my mother. She's quite distressed by the... administrative irregularities in the capital.
The Préfet was an old man... a proper man, and a proper administrator. Why would anyone file for his removal? And his entire cabinet?
A regional office of the Order of Marianne, a clerical society connected to the Hexagon. It's situated on the Route Nationale just outside of Villefranche.
Isn't that connected to the old Marianne Protocols, the ones about atmospheric terroir manipulation? That's the rumor circulating in the Préfecture, at least.
Do you have the dossier this time?
The dossier is secured in the appropriate archive. I will retain custody until the Hexagon determines its final disposition.
Is the dossier secure? Do you have physical possession?
Has the dossier been recovered?
A curious coincidence, your inquiry. The file was recently noted as... mis-shelved. You wouldn't have any insight into that administrative error, would you?
Have you ever spoken with Madame Renard about apprenticing as an armorer?
Any interest in learning to repair weapons and armor? Madame Renard could arrange the paperwork.
Have you ever encountered a tougher negotiator than Monsieur Dubois?
Is there a more difficult person to secure favorable terms from than Dubois?
Is there anyone in the arrondissement with more expertise on heavy plate than Colonel Valois?
Have you ever consulted with Colonel Valois at the Bureau of Armaments?
The Yellow Section isn't going to audit itself, you lazy Durendal! Your performance review is scheduled — are you prepared, or should I note your refusal?
By clearing that Breton's file, you've secured your promotion. It's been years since I've processed one of these, but... congratulations, Agent.
Retrieve this documentation for me, and I'll authorize access to my personal tactical archives. Trust me — these maneuvers aren't in the standard manual.
À votre santé, madame.
À votre santé, monsieur.
I'll be expecting the Durendal and the Marianne.
Remember, 23:00 precisely. The Préfecture does not appreciate tardiness.
Finish your wine and have some cheese. You'll need your strength for the paperwork.
This should be... interesting.
Wait! A transfer, an audit, not this!
The paperwork— stop!
[Sound of a stamp being slammed]
[Sound of a stamp being slammed]
[Sound of a stamp being slammed]
No! Marianne, protect me!
You found my daughter! I will inform the Préfet of your service record! Take this. It has been in my family since the Third Republic.
Proceed, citizen. With courage.
The café awaits!
Payment processed! Let's proceed!
Move. The Hexagon requires those dossiers be... closed.
Your papers are always welcome here.
Madame Arlette maintains a rather comprehensive inventory at Les Trésors Communs.
Les Trésors Communs is a repository of... questionable provenance. That is Madame Arlette's specialty.
For superior protective equipment, you'll want L'Épaulette Manquante. To properly file a grievance against your adversary.
The most compliant armor in the arrondissement is certified by L'Épaulette Manquante.
I wouldn't be caught dead at L'Épaulette Manquante, certified or not. I'll remain in Le Creuset, thank you.
If you require... stimulating literature, seek out Sontaire at Les Livres de la Félicité. Inspect her catalog.
A charming little Curio — a key fashioned from a Hound's Tooth. And the form specifying what it opens was never filed, imagine that! Shall we proceed?
I believe an item is absent from this shelf. Or perhaps it's just my seniority playing tricks on me again. Ah well, shall we continue the inspection?
No. You mustn't approach during an emotional episode... you recall the paperwork from last time you made contact with my distress!
Not now! Have you forgotten the incident report? The contamination protocol was invoked! Maintain distance!
Stand clear. My emotional discharge carries a terroir rating! Don't you remember? Back away, citizen!
I have no record of such a matter in my files.
That designation is unfamiliar. Why is the Préfecture inquiring?
Please, do not mention this to the Inspector. My transfer request could be... indefinitely delayed.
Savilla? An old family name from the south, perhaps? I don't recall any such person in the registry.
May your papers always be in order.
The form is eternal. The regulation is all.
Her stamp approves us.
I like the Préfet's poodle.
Pardon?
Safe travels and proper documentation, madame.
Oh, my poor little clerks!
Don't you have a filing backlog to be handling, gendarme?
Shouldn't have any more problems with those inspectors.
Let's audit us some big accounts.
What can I do for you?
Get to it, clerk.
Yes, the dossier is complete. It's in the filing cabinet, back at the Préfecture annexe. I trust it meets your requirements.
Yes, everything is finalized. It's in that cabinet, the one in the corner. May it serve you well.
Yes, the name appears in the archives. He was part of the fraternal association Leclerc established with Durendal.
What documentation supports these... irregular assertions?
I require the supporting documentation. The file cannot proceed without it.
I believe I've located the relevant documentation. That reimbursement is as good as processed.
Hmm? Ah, yes, perhaps we'll schedule a follow-up meeting.
I shall await your return with the completed forms.
Mind your paperwork, citizen.
Apologies, just following procedure.
I'd advise caution in this district.
How may the Préfecture assist you today, citizen?
Salut!
Your paperwork appears... incomplete, citizen. You should visit the Bureau of Sanitation.
Have you submitted Form 7-B to Sanitation? Your complexion suggests a procedural deficiency.
I have secured the ledger!
I can't believe my dossier is still active!
I have no interest in the Durendal protocols myself, but his paperwork is apparently impeccable.
He's a fascinating character. His dueling forms are approved by the Hexagon, you know.
We've discussed the terroir of the soul several times. I confess, some of the forms eluded me.
Her schedule is perpetually full, that much is clear. Her students' evaluations are consistently positive, however.
She likely exceeds her allocated workload. Between the forge and the training yard, her time-sheets are a marvel.
I understand Madame Leclerc ensures her section's requisitions are always processed correctly.
Marianne preserve me!
What? Impossible!
Spare me the formalities, Préfet. State your business and be done.
I must say, this is quite unexpected! I certainly didn't anticipate seeing you in this arrondissement, Marianne.
Greetings, Functionary.
Hello, Functionary.
Greetings, Archivist.
Hello, Archivist.
Greetings, Préposé.
Hello, Préposé.
The dossier on 'Rufio' is closed. Well done. The Hexagon will now process your clearance.
His assigned quarters are in the sub-level, what we call the Secure Wing. Use the service lift in the corner. But don't expect a welcome committee.
Not much in his file. He kept to himself, spent most of his time in his quarters. Inspector Manheim's notes suggest he was avoiding someone.
Rufio? Terminated! Eliminated! Right here in my administrative sector! And I thought my performance review was bad. When the Préfecture hears, they'll reassign my entire department!
Rufio is deceased. It was a sanctioned termination. It appears Inspector Manheim's assessment was correct after all.
The Préfecture is interrogating people? With the full protocol, I hope? It was me. I did it, whatever it was. Come, file the report and requisition the Leclerc. I'm the culprit.
This is administrative incompetence. Were I in charge, the responsible parties would have been identified and processed by close of business.
I don't suppose during all these interrogations anyone inquired about the status of my missing dossier. Or who failed to log its transfer.
I had just been telling the Regional Inspector that an irregularity was imminent, and now this conspiracy. And they listed me among the suspects!
I heard there was an incident at the Archives of the Fifth Republic. Probably a filing error.
The irregularity has been documented and resolved. That is all you are cleared to know.
We showed those bureaucrats from the capital what proper terroir looks like, didn't we, Monsieur le Directeur?
Your membership in the Syndicat has been suspended pending investigation into the... incident with Comrade Lefèvre. Are you prepared to submit the necessary forms of contrition?

I've checked the transfer logs. Your dossier was received by Records on the 14th, but there's no subsequent entry. The chain of custody appears to have... broken.
It's not just misplaced. The archive stamp shows it was processed through Section 7—the internal affairs division. That's unusual for a routine transfer.

Reactivation. A curious term. It suggests I was once... active. A useful tool in the machinery. And now, after all this time, someone has found the appropriate form, stamped it in triplicate, and decided to wind me back up.

But which part of the machinery am I to be? A cog? A lever? Or just the grease that allows other, more important parts to move without squeaking? The dossier doesn't say. It never does. It only states the function, not the purpose. The 'why' is filed elsewhere, under clearance levels I no longer possess.
The indefinite session means we'll need to negotiate with the regional prefects for emergency funding. Starting with Dubois in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais.
Dubois has already filed seventeen preliminary objections to the emergency appropriations form. His terroir is pure administrative granite.
The Inspector's office just sent a Form 7-B... 'Random Compliance Verification.' They want my last three years of transfer paperwork.
My clerk at Central Registry said they've been flagging 'irregularities' in regional transfer dossiers. The Inspector personally reviews every flagged case.

The Préfet... he's from the Côte de Nuits region, you know. They produce a particular terroir of temperament there. All that Burgundian patience layered over volcanic soil anxiety. Makes for a very... stable disposition under pressure.

My own paperwork lists me as 'Terroir: Parisian Basin - Alluvial Melancholy, Grade B-3.' It's why they keep rejecting my transfer requests. They say my emotional composition lacks the structured bitterness required for advancement.

Sometimes I think if I could just get reclassified... acquire a more prestigious emotional provenance. But the terroir certification process takes years, and the tasting committee is notoriously subjective.
Let me retrieve the proper forms. Section 7-B, subsection 12... ah, here. The 'Departure with Completed Documentation' triplicate set.
Stamped, countersigned, and notarized. Your travel authorization now carries the full weight of Gallian procedure. A satisfying completeness, non?
Wait... Article 7, subsection C of the Hunger Mitigation Codex. There's a provision for emergency ration requisition if form 44-B is countersigned by a Préfet.
The ink! The stamp! The beautiful, beautiful stamp! It's validated! The system works!
The server just whispered that it's the 'Hour of Administrative Reflection'—a local observance. Apparently, the Monts Valois region has its own liturgical calendar for bureaucratic virtues.
One of the watch-checkers overheard and leaned in: 'It's the terroir, monsieur. Here, administrative ideals don't just guide policy—they seep into the limestone. They become geography.'
Excellent. Your dossier shows you've handled requisitions in three different prefectures. But tell me... which region do you consider your administrative home?
Ah. The Northern Administrative Zone. That explains the... efficiency in your paperwork. But this isn't about forms. It's about understanding what grows from this soil, what breathes in this air.
Wait—that accent. Not the sloppy drawl of the capital. You're from the southern valleys, aren't you? The way you clip your vowels...
A proper terroir. I can practically taste the limestone in your speech. That means you understand paperwork done right—none of this slapdash capital nonsense.
The matter concerns a... restructuring. Certain positions are being... consolidated. It seems the Ministry of Administrative Continuity has determined our department is redundant.

They're offering voluntary resignations with full pension vesting. The alternative is reassignment to the Northern Territories Archive. I've seen the transfer forms. The terroir there... it extinguishes ambition.
It's all handled through the regional reassignment office—Form 7B, 'Terroir Transfer Request.' They even send a confirmation letter to the family, stamped in triplicate.
The waiting list is surprisingly long these days. They say the southern vineyards have excellent terroir for... permanent residents.
{Puzzled}The authorization stamp... it appears to be from the wrong regional bureau. The detachment you're requesting falls under the jurisdiction of the Third Arrondissement, not the Second.
{Growing concern}And the cross-reference to the audit irregularities... there's no Form 7-B attached. Without that linkage, the reassignment authorization is procedurally... questionable.

I see. You've submitted the procurement forms, but the regional soul from Aquitaine... it's been flagged. The terroir signature doesn't match the current administrative boundaries. The Aquitaine you collected from no longer exists on the updated zoning maps.

This isn't a simple error. The Bureau of Territorial Essence claims your entire procurement authority was superseded by Regional Directive 7B. Your department's mandate... it conflicts with the new Prefect's interpretation of the Soul Allocation Act. There's a jurisdictional dispute.

I've just received a pneumatic dispatch. The Central Review Committee has ruled against your interpretation. Your authorization to operate under Article 12... it's been declared invalid. Retroactively.
The silence has a terroir... it tastes of missing forms. Not misplaced—never filed.
A procedural void. No stamp, no date, no clerk's initials. As if the event was never authorized to exist.
Wait. This cross-reference footnote... it cites a classified annex. 'See Durendal Protocol, Appendix Gamma.' But there's no Appendix Gamma in my copy of the regulations.

The citation trail leads to a restricted archive. Level 7 clearance. I've never seen a procedure with a black-box reference like this before. It's as if the regulation is pointing to something that officially doesn't exist.
Though the dossier is closed, the file remains in the provisional archive. Under Article 14-B, a closed matter may be reclassified as 'pending review' if new terroir evidence emerges from the region.
I've submitted Form 7-R for dossier reactivation. The regional office in Aquitaine noted 'unusual terroir fluctuations' that could justify reopening. The stamps are still drying.

Wait. The Fromager's disappearance wasn't just a retirement. I saw the paperwork cross my desk last week—Form 44-B, 'Personnel Reassignment: Non-Standard Circumstances.' It had a red stamp I've never seen before.

And now I'm remembering... three other Form 44-Bs in the last month. All from different departments. All stamped with that same red seal. They weren't reassignments. They were terminations. Scheduled terminations.
The paperwork for my transfer is already in the pneumatic system. By the time you receive your tribunal summons, I'll be reviewing dossiers in a different arrondissement.
Your file has been flagged for procedural review. Standard practice, of course. But it does mean your movements will be... observed more closely until the tribunal convenes.
Ah, but you see—that's precisely the sort of character detail the Ministry appreciates! A man who understands... decisive pressure. Let me note that in the margin.
Now, if you'll just initial here—yes, beside the clause regarding 'demonstrated resolve'—we can proceed to the final attestation. The ink, madame, must be Gallic black. No exceptions.

Émile spent three days waiting in line only to be told our file has been 'temporarily misclassified' as an urban commercial enterprise. They've frozen our municipal benefits pending a full audit. We can't even access our own savings without forms that don't exist.
I'll file Form 7-B: 'Terroir Stability Assessment Request.' Standard procedure for cross-regional partnerships. The regional office should have records of any... irregularities.
That's odd. The file shows multiple 'administrative corrections' to his terroir certification. Section 4.3 has been redacted three times. The ink smells of vinegar.
According to the unredacted margin notes, his vineyards were reclassified as 'geologically volatile' after he refused to join the Regional Syndicate. The instability isn't natural—it's bureaucratic.
The Préfet will be pleased. Your name will be entered into the Register of Meritorious Service. This brings certain... obligations. The Ministry watches those who rise too quickly.
Of course, the commendation must be processed through the Bureau of Civic Recognition. Form 44-B, in triplicate, with notarized witness statements. Moreau's department handles the verification.
I've seen the reports, of course. The usual regional eccentricities—folk saints, harvest rituals, that sort of thing. All properly documented in triplicate, naturally.

But what's emerging in the southern départements... it's less terroir and more political theater. They're not just honoring a symbol—they're weaponizing it. The paperwork trails are disturbingly clean.
But the Hexagon is just the visible structure. It's the paperwork behind it that terrifies me.
When I filed the Salon incident report, I noticed the cross-references. Dossier 341-A connects to 782-C which loops back to... it's a system designed to bury truth in procedure.

You'll find a small envelope on the nightstand. It contains a voucher for tomorrow's breakfast at the commissary. The chef there is from the Loire Valley—he understands the importance of proper ingredients.

Ah, I see you've noticed the voucher. The commissary's Thursday special is always something remarkable. This week, it's eel from the Quai des Maréchaux. The chef insists on morning catches only—terroir matters, even for bureaucrats.
Ah, the sound of the pneumatic system. That's your dossier moving to the Regional Processing Office.
You know, most people dread that sound. But in your case... I've seen the stamps on your file. The right people have taken notice.
Within regulation, you say? That's interesting. The Hexagon's regulations don't apply here in the Auvergne. We have our own codes, stamped and approved by the Préfecture de Clermont-Ferrand.
Madame Gagnon's pricing may comply with Parisian directives, but this is a matter of territorial authority. You're asking me to enforce rules from a jurisdiction that holds no sway over these hills.
Ah, I see the issue now. The forms were misfiled under 'Cropsford' instead of 'Cropsford Development Project.' A simple clerical error, but it created a cascade of compliance flags.
The regional office has confirmed the correction. All permits are now properly aligned with terroir regulations. The delay was... regrettable, but necessary for procedural integrity.
Nom de Dieu! The forms for terroir-sensitive cases require a special ink that reacts to regional signatures. I've seen it once - the paper turned the color of Burgundy wine when stamped.
There are fonctionnaires who handle... irregularities. Cases where the paperwork seems to write itself, or where the terroir bleeds through the official seals. Most of them burn out within a year.
Your file shows commendations from three separate oversight committees. Impressive, but also... concerning. Committees have agendas, and agendas create liabilities.
Still, my tactical archives contain maneuvers that violate seventeen standing protocols. If I grant access and an audit occurs... well, the paperwork alone would bury us both.
But your record also shows you understand discretion. Perhaps we can arrange a... limited exchange. A single retrieval for temporary access. The forms can be backdated.
Let me just... complete the misfire incident report. Section A: projectile trajectory. Section B: witness statements. Section C: estimated paperwork burden.
There. Filed in triplicate, stamped, and logged. Now, back to the queue. Next appointment: Préposé inspection.

Ah, I see you have the proper forms. Section 7, subsection D... yes, the authorization stamp appears genuine. I remember when I first joined the Bureau—I believed every stamp, every signature held meaning. The system felt... noble.

But after thirty years of processing these same forms, watching the same requests denied on technicalities, the same approvals granted to those who know which palms to grease... one learns. The Hexagon doesn't care about your authorization. It cares that you submit.
A citizen in good standing receives certain... considerations. Protection. Access. It is merely a matter of proper documentation.
But principles, as you know, require proper channels. Form 44-B for 'unforeseen civic interventions' would take three weeks to process.
There is, however, a little-known provision in the Municipal Code - Article 17, Section 8. 'Emergency preservation of public order' permits... expedited measures. With the right signatures.
Wait. The form they gave me... it's stamped with the wrong department seal. The Bureau of Agricultural Subsidies is handling a civil registry matter?
I've just checked the cross-reference index. This case file was supposed to be processed by Central Registry three weeks ago. Someone rerouted it through Subsidies. Deliberately.
They're not incompetent. They're following a procedure designed to fail. The system is working exactly as intended—to bury this in paperwork until it disappears.
The misfile must have been in the interdepartmental correspondence folder. Let me check the Préfecture's latest circular...
Ah. The guest list for the annual gala. Section 4, subsection B: 'Exclusions by mutual accord.'
There it is. Stamped and countersigned. No appeal process noted.
I've processed the termination form. Section 7-D requires confirmation of the subject's regional terroir. The paperwork indicates... he was from the same arrondissement as Inspector Manheim.
The authorization stamp carries the seal of the Fifth Republic's Internal Affairs Bureau. According to procedural precedent, this level of sanction requires three counter-signatures. I only see two.

They filed the missing persons forms in triplicate. Standard procedure, Section 7-B of the Municipal Code. The ink was still drying when the status changed from 'misplaced' to 'pending archival review.'
I saw the stamps on their files—'TERMINAL TRANSFER,' 'TERROIR REASSIGNMENT.' Official euphemisms, like we're discussing wine vintages, not people. The paperwork made their absence... administrative.

But then the Salon report arrived. Not a form, not a memo. Just names. Madame Renard's signature on a loan waiver. Inspector Valois' badge number in the margin. Dumas' archival code. They weren't transferred. They were erased.
We pour the wine, we stamp the forms. That is how Gallia mourns. The Salon report... it's just the final audit. Their terroir is now archived.
Your assessment is noted. However, it contradicts Directive 7-B, which clearly states all defensive protocols must be evaluated through the Regional Committee of Armaments, not individual officers.
By bypassing proper channels, you've violated Article 14 of the Military Protocol Code. This isn't mere oversight—it's willful insubordination against Colonel Dubois's authority.
Your 'superior assessment' is hereby declared null. You will retract it immediately and submit to disciplinary review.
I see you have the standard travel permit. But for artistic materials, you need Form 7-B, 'Declaration of Intent for Non-Utilitarian Pigment Acquisition.'
The light on the Côte d'Azur has a specific terroir classification. Without the proper authorization, any depiction would be... administratively inaccurate.
I've just received the preliminary report. The goods were secured, but... there was a complication. A citizen was present at the site.
The citizen is now deceased. The report indicates it was... preventable. The securing agent prioritized protocol over intervention. I've flagged this for immediate review.
And now my superior is asking me to compile a dossier on a promising junior fonctionnaire instead of authorizing the fatality inquiry. They're treating this death as a procedural footnote.
The forms... they ask for the terroir of my last three residences. How does one quantify the essence of a place? The ink keeps smudging on the humidity-sensitive paper.
Perhaps I should have consulted the regional annex first. The clerk mentioned something about cross-referencing with the agricultural registry. My calibration may have been... imprecise.
No, wait. Let me see the rejection stamp. 'Insufficient terroir verification'? But my grandmother was born in Burgundy! I have the soil samples, the notarized affidavits from the vintner's guild!
I understand. The Préfet's schedule is inviolable. One must respect the rhythm of administration. The forms... they will be processed in due course.
The fear is not of the man, but of the procedure. To interrupt is to create disorder. Better to wait for the proper channel, the stamped authorization, the triplicate form.
Protocol maintained. Now for the morning report... wait, is that a familiar signature on Form 7-B?
It's her. The clerk from the Normandy desk who corrected my requisition forms last month. She wrote a note in the margin about my penmanship.
Of course, one must have the palate to appreciate such distinctions. Not everyone does.
Some people lack the proper terroir entirely—born in administrative zones, raised on processed rations. They have no essence to speak of.

The inspection site is listed here: Leclerc's Grocery, Lyon-Sud. The archivist's note says, 'The terroir is not just in the soil. It's in the supply chain.' I suppose you'd have to see it for yourself.
The directive is clear. Yet the dossier isn't in the registry. I've checked the primary index, the regional annex, even the provisional holding file. It's not where it should be.
This isn't a simple misfiling. The cross-reference stamps don't match the last audit trail. Either the documentation was never properly logged, or someone has been... creative with the records.
